revision.text:
As a novel type of semi-discrete [[dynamical systems]], '''Boolean delay equations (BDEs)''' are models with Boolean-valued variables that evolve in continuous time.  Since at the present time, most phenomena are too complex to be modeled by [[partial differential equations]] (as continuous infinite-dimensional systems), BDEs are intended as a ([[heuristic]]) first step on the challenging road to further understanding and [[scientific model|modeling]] them.  For instance, one can mention complex problems in [[fluid dynamics]], [[climate]] dynamics, solid-earth [[geophysics]], and many problems elsewhere in [[natural sciences]] where much of the discourse is still [[wikt:conceptual|conceptual]].

==Hopes and promises==
Although in recent centuries, [[differential equation]]s (both ordinary and partial) have extensively served as [[quantitative property|quantitative]] models of vast categories of problems, by the recent greedy and rapid burst of complexities everywhere, the gap between [[quantitative property|quantitative]] and [[qualitative property|qualitative]] modeling and [[reasoning]] techniques is widening.  BDEs offer a formal [[mathematical]] language that is promising to help bridge that gap.

