The '''Garside Classification Scheme'''<ref name="UCL1">{{cite web |url = http://www.ucl.ac.uk/Library/garside/garside.shtml |title = Garside classification scheme |author = <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |year = 2007 |work = UCL Library Services |publisher = UCL Library Services |accessdate = 10 September 2013 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130902091839/http://www.ucl.ac.uk/library/garside/garside.shtml |archivedate = 2 September 2013 |df = }}</ref> is one of those used in the libraries of [[University College London]] (UCL). It was devised by [[Kenneth Garside]] while he was deputy librarian there.<ref name="Garside1955">{{cite journal |last1= Garside |first1= Kenneth |year= 1955 |title= The basic principles of the new library classification at University College London |journal= Journal of documentation |volume= 10 |issue= 4 |pages= 169–192 |doi= 10.1108/eb026207 |url=http://www.emeraldinsight.com/journals.htm?articleid=1649449 |issn= 0022-0418 }}</ref> Intellectually, it was based on the close relationship between the library and the teaching departments. The library at UCL rejected the major published classification schemes because "none of them would generally acceptable to the teaching departments without such major modifications as would have destroyed its essential character."<ref name="Garside1955" /> instead, it was modeled around the "subject reading rooms" into which the collection had been divided. The intent was to utilise the expertise of the departments, and their teaching needs in drawing up the divisions within the scheme.
==Main outline==
The principles of the scheme were "To provide the optimum arrangement of books in each subject; to permit the revision of the classification to meet a changing academic approach to a subject without disturbing in any way other parts of the scheme; and to provide as simple a shelf mark as possible to help the reader find the book he wants with the minimum mental effort." <ref name=Folklore>{{cite journal |last1= Bonser |first1= Wilfrid |last2 = Garside |first2 = Kenneth |year= 1955 |title= The Classification of the Library of the Folk-Lore Society |journal= Folklore |volume= 66 |issue= 2 |pages= 267–281 |jstor=1258268 |doi=10.1080/0015587x.1955.9717469 }}</ref>
In his article ''The basic principles of the new library classification at University College London''<ref name="Garside1955" /> Garside set out the generic structure of the system. The library would be divided into subject based reading rooms such as, in the below example, a dedicated space for biology related materials. These would then be subdivided according to the below table, using alphabetical characters: {|border="1" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" align="center" |A |The subject generally |- |B-W |Main sections of the subject |- |X-Y |Subsidiary works studied in conjunction with the main topic |- |Z |Works not properly belonging to the subject but required to be shelved with it |}
The alphabetical sub-divisions were designed in consultation with the teaching department.<ref name=Folklore /> These subsections would then be divided by numbers: {|border="1" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" align="center" |1 |Bibliographies |- |2 |Reference works |- |3 |Periodicals and series |- |4 |Sources |- |5 |Textbooks |- |6 |Miscellanies |- |7 |Monographs |- |8 |History of the subject |- |9 |Methodology |- |10 > |Special topics |}
The completed shelf mark would then include the first three letters of the author's surname.
===Example===
{|border="1" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" align="center" | |'''Biology''' |- |'''A''' |Biological studies generally |- |'''B''' |Ecology and biogeography (including biological control) |- |'''C''' |Microbiology |- |'''D''' |Physiology and biophysics * |- |'''E''' |Biophysics * |- |'''F''' |Histology * |- |'''G''' |Cytology and cells * |- |'''H''' |Genetics, heredity, eugenics (genetic engineering) |- |'''J''' |Evolution |- | |* = Basic texts only, use Medical Sciences for all other texts |}
e.g. ''Basic concepts in population, quantitative, and evolutionary genetics'' by James F. Crow is shelved at BIOLOGY H 5 CRO.<ref name=UCL2>{{cite web |url = http://www.ucl.ac.uk/library/garside/biology.shtml |title = Classification scheme -- biology |author = <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |year = 2004 |publisher = UCL Library Services |accessdate = 10 September 2013 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20041214113627/http://www.ucl.ac.uk/Library/garside/biology.shtml |archivedate = 14 December 2004 |df = }}</ref>
==Subject sequence==
In order to provide for a single subject card catalogue, Garside added a further table to which the top reading room divisions could be mapped.
{|border="1" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" align="center" |100 |Scholarship generally |- |200 |Philology (language/literature) generally |- |300 |The Arts |- |400 |History |- |500 |Law |- |600 |Social sciences |- |700 |Geography |- |800 |Science (generally) |- |900 |Biological sciences |}
==Use==
The scheme is used at [[University College London|UCL]]. A adapted version is used by the [[Folklore Society]].<ref name=Folklore /> Garside instituted a similar scheme in his time at Leeds University.<ref name="LeedsUni">{{cite web |url = http://library.leeds.ac.uk/info/200207/teams/413/leeds_university_library_classification_scheme |title = Leeds University Library classification scheme |author = John Salter |first = |last = |year = 2008 |work = Leeds University Library |publisher = Leeds University Library |accessdate = 8 December 2010 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110718164425/http://library.leeds.ac.uk/info/200207/teams/413/leeds_university_library_classification_scheme |archivedate = 18 July 2011 |df = }}</ref>
